## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | Details |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 🔴 **Breaking** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | 🟡 Deprecated | Works but unreliable — only interrupts `WaitSleepJoin` state |
| Race condition | 🔴 **Bug** | Multiple `Enqueue` calls before `Dequeue` → lost signals. `Reset()` clears the event even when items remain |
| No graceful shutdown | 🟡 Design | No cancellation token; relies on hard abort |
| Manual thread + lock | 🟡 Modernize | `Channel<T>` replaces all of this with backpressure built in |

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync yields items as they arrive; blocks asynchronously
        // when empty; completes when the writer is closed.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        // 1. Signal the writer is done — RunLoopAsync will drain and exit
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        if (_runTask is not null)
        {
            // 2. Give it time to drain gracefully
            using var timeoutCts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            try
            {
                await _runTask.WaitAsync(timeoutCts.Token);
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // 3. Force cancel if drain takes too long
                await _cts.CancelAsync();
                try { await _runTask; }
                catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
            }
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### Key Changes Explained

**`Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`**
All three primitives collapse into one. `ReadAllAsync` blocks asynchronously when empty and wakes on write — no signal management, no race condition.

**`CancellationToken` replaces `Abort`/`Interrupt`**
Cooperative cancellation is the only supported model in .NET 5+. `Thread.Abort()` will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime.

**`IAsyncDisposable` replaces `Stop()`**
Enables `await using var processor = new EventProcessor();` and integrates with DI containers.

### Common Migration Pitfalls

1. **Don't just delete `Thread.Abort()`** — you need a cooperative replacement (`CancellationToken`), or the thread will never stop.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt()` still compiles** but only throws if the thread is in `WaitSleepJoin`. If it's mid-`Handle()`, the interrupt is deferred silently.
3. **The original race condition**: two fast `Enqueue` calls → one `Set()` is lost after `Reset()` → second item stuck in queue. `Channel<T>` eliminates this entirely.
4. **`BlockingCollection<T>`** is a valid intermediate step if you want to keep synchronous threads, but `Channel<T>` is the modern default and supports async throughout.
